the 20 and 30 range. \xA0Choosing \xA0pre tied, or snelled, hooks can save time and frustration. \xA0Also, look for hooks with a longer shank as these are easier to remove from the mouth of the fish. Japanese hooks, such as those used for catching tanago, a species of bitterling, are an ideal choice."), mdx("p", null, "Linha\nLine should be extremely light since most small fish have great eyesight and will not bite if they are spooked. \xA0Again, start by looking for line in the fly fishing tackle section. Find a high quality small diameter tippet. \xA0An alternative is ice fishing line. However, this is usually weaker and has a larger diameter for the same pound test. \xA0These small lines can be attached as a leader on to a spinning rod. \xA0A very small weight pinched at about three to five inches above the hook will help control bait and keep the line steady in wind.\xA0 Japanese equipment that is specialized for tanago can also be used, such as the bitterling kit listed below, and is best in murky conditions"), mdx("p", null, "B\xF3ia"), mdx("p", null, "Confeccionar usando madeira balsa"), mdx("p", null, "Outros"), mdx("p", null, "Worms work great for micro fishing. \xA0Many micro fish have very small mouths so the smallest piece of worm you can get on the hook is ideal. \xA0Using your finger nail, or clippers, will be your best options for preparing the bait. \xA0Maggots, blood worms, and gluten also work for micro fishing. \xA0When necessity dictates, a wide variety of other food sources can also work as bait for catching minnows. Some good baits you can purchase at the grocery store are bread, cheese, and imitation crab.\nThe depth of the bait in the water is important and will determine what species of fish you will catch. \xA0If the bait is teased on the surface of the water you will attract aggressive topminnows and other species that primarily feed at this level. \xA0Letting the bait fall to the bed of the pool or stream will entice benthic feeders such as darters and madtom. Time of day, swiftness of current, structures, and substrate are also factors to consider when targeting micro fish. \xA0Researching habitats and feeding traits of fish will increase your chances of landing the right species."), mdx("p", null, "Microfishing photo tank"), mdx("p", null, "Removedor de anzol usando uma agulha bem grande com a ponta de cima cordada pregada em uma b\xF3ia"), mdx("p", null, "Suporte pra linhas com anzol"), mdx("p", null, "livro identifica\xE7\xE3o peixes"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("h3", {
